{"title_page": "Geisenhausen", "text_new": "{{Infobox German location\n|image_coa            = Geisenhausen LA coat of arms.svg\n|image_photo      = Pfarrkirche Geisenhausen-2.JPG\n|image_caption    = Church of Saint Martin in Geisenhausen\n|coordinates       = {{coord|48|28|N|12|15|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|image_plan = Geisenhausen in LA.svg\n|state        = Bayern\n|region  = Lower Bavaria\n|district         = Landshut\n|elevation              = 460\n|area            = 62.54\n|postal_code               = 84144\n|area_code           = 08743\n|licence               = LA\n|Gemeindeschl\u00fcssel = 09274134\n|website           = [http://www.geisenhausen.de/ www.geisenhausen.de]\n|mayor     = Josef Reff\n|party            = FW\n}}\n'''Geisenhausen''' is a municipality with [[market town]] status in the [[Landshut (district)|district of Landshut]], in [[Bavaria]], [[Germany]]. It is situated 14&nbsp;km southeast of [[Landshut]] in the valley of the [[Vils (Danube)|Kleine Vils]].\n\n== History ==\nGeisenhausen was first mentioned in a document in 980 and received market rights in 1393.\n\n== Administrative division ==\n*Albanstetten\n*Diemannskirchen\n*H\u00f6rlkam\n*Hermannskirchen\n*Holzhausen\n*Geisenhausen\n*Salksdorf\n*Johannesbergham\n*Westersbergham\n*Stephansbergham\n*Irlach\n\n== Sights ==\nThe parish church St. Martin from the second half of the 15th century is a brick building in [[Gothic architecture|gothic]] style similar to its larger [[St. Martin, Landshut|namesake in Landshut]]. Historic middle-class houses line part of market square and main road. The church of St. Theobald was a destiny of pilgrimages from about 1390 to 1790.\n\n== Infrastructure ==\nGeisenhausen is linked with the rail system of the Deutsche Bahn. The [[Bundesstra\u00dfe 299]], an important road, bypasses the market town.\n\n== Periodic events ==\n*[[Rosenmontag]]szug (Rose Monday Parade) of the [[carnival]] club Tollemogei\n*Farmers' market\n*Fair of the B\u00fcrger- und Gewerbeverein (citizens and business association) at the weekend of Whitsun\n\n== Famous citizens ==\n* [[G\u00fcnter Eich]] (1907-1972), writer\n* [[Martin Fl\u00f6rchinger]] (1909\u20132004), actor\n* [[Thomas Schmid (Autor)|Thomas Schmid]] (1960), writer\n* [[Johannes Schmid]] (1973), stage director\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.Geisenhausen.de/}}\n\n{{Cities and towns in Landshut (district)}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Landshut (district)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox German location\n|image_coa            = Geisenhausen LA coat of arms.svg\n|image_photo      = Pfarrkirche Geisenhausen-2.JPG\n|image_caption    = Church of Saint Martin in Geisenhausen\n|coordinates       = {{coord|48|28|N|12|15|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|image_plan = Geisenhausen in LA.svg\n|state        = Bayern\n|region  = Lower Bavaria\n|district         = Landshut\n|elevation              = 460\n|area            = 62.54\n|pop_dens          = 101\n|postal_code               = 84144\n|area_code           = 08743\n|licence               = LA\n|Gemeindeschl\u00fcssel = 09274134\n|Stra\u00dfe            = \n|website           = [http://www.geisenhausen.de/ www.geisenhausen.de]\n|mayor     = Josef Reff\n|party            = FW\n}}\n'''Geisenhausen''' is a municipality with [[market town]] status in the [[Landshut (district)|district of Landshut]], in [[Bavaria]], [[Germany]]. It is situated 14&nbsp;km southeast of [[Landshut]] in the valley of the [[Vils (Danube)|Kleine Vils]].\n\n== History ==\nGeisenhausen was first mentioned in a document in 980 and received market rights in 1393.\n\n== Administrative division ==\n*Albanstetten\n*Diemannskirchen\n*H\u00f6rlkam\n*Hermannskirchen\n*Holzhausen\n*Geisenhausen\n*Salksdorf\n*Johannesbergham\n*Westersbergham\n*Stephansbergham\n*Irlach\n\n== Sights ==\nThe parish church St. Martin from the second half of the 15th century is a brick building in [[Gothic architecture|gothic]] style similar to its larger [[St. Martin, Landshut|namesake in Landshut]]. Historic middle-class houses line part of market square and main road. The church of St. Theobald was a destiny of pilgrimages from about 1390 to 1790.\n\n== Infrastructure ==\nGeisenhausen is linked with the rail system of the Deutsche Bahn. The [[Bundesstra\u00dfe 299]], an important road, bypasses the market town.\n\n== Periodic events ==\n*[[Rosenmontag]]szug (Rose Monday Parade) of the [[carnival]] club Tollemogei\n*Farmers' market\n*Fair of the B\u00fcrger- und Gewerbeverein (citizens and business association) at the weekend of Whitsun\n\n== Famous citizens ==\n* [[G\u00fcnter Eich]] (1907-1972), writer\n* [[Martin Fl\u00f6rchinger]] (1909\u20132004), actor\n* [[Thomas Schmid (Autor)|Thomas Schmid]] (1960), writer\n* [[Johannes Schmid]] (1973), stage director\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.Geisenhausen.de/}}\n\n{{Cities and towns in Landshut (district)}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Landshut (district)]]\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geisenhausen"}
